JD 17:

Key Responsibilities
1. Category Strategy & Planning

Develop, own, and execute global and regional category strategies for:

External Manufacturing (CMO/CDMO)

Primary & Secondary Packaging

Medical Affairs Evidence Generation (RWE, NIS, Clinical Data Acquisition)

Translate global divisional procurement strategies into sub-category and country-specific execution plans.

Align category strategies with business priorities, product pipelines, lifecycle stages, and market expansion plans.

Build multi-year sourcing roadmaps covering cost, capacity, risk, compliance, and innovation levers.

Continuously monitor supplier market dynamics, capacity trends, pricing movements, and regulatory changes.

2. Strategic Sourcing & Supplier Selection

Lead end-to-end strategic sourcing activities including RFI/RFP/RFQ, technical-commercial evaluations, and supplier selection.

Support sourcing for:

CMOs/CDMOs (drug substance, drug product, fill-finish)

Packaging partners (primary, secondary, labeling)

CROs, data providers, registries for Medical Affairs evidence generation

Define sourcing specifications, demand assumptions, and service models in collaboration with cross-functional stakeholders.

Identify, qualify, and onboard regulatory-approved suppliers (EU-GMP, USFDA, PIC/S, TGA, ANVISA, MCC).

3. Contracting & Commercial Governance

Lead negotiation and execution of:

Master Service Agreements (MSAs)

Statements of Work (SoWs)

Supply Agreements and Amendments

Own commercial negotiations covering pricing, service fees, payment milestones, volume commitments, and performance incentives.

Ensure contracts clearly define scope, quality responsibilities, regulatory obligations, escalation mechanisms, and KPIs.

Ensure contract terms are consistently applied across regions and business units.

4. Supplier Relationship & Performance Management

Segment suppliers and define Supplier Relationship Management (SRM) models for strategic, preferred, and transactional partners.

Act as the primary interface for key CMOs, packaging partners, and evidence-generation vendors.

Drive Monthly / Quarterly Business Reviews (MBRs/QBRs) with senior supplier leadership.

Track supplier KPIs across OTIF, quality, compliance, cost, service, and innovation.

Lead supplier issue resolution, escalation management, and corrective action planning.

5. Risk Management & Supply Assurance

Identify and proactively mitigate supply, quality, regulatory, and business risks across the supplier base.

Develop N-level and N-1 supply chain risk assessments and mitigation strategies.

Support product transfers, site changes, alternate source development, and in-sourcing initiatives.

Ensure continuity of supply across regulated, emerging, and rest-of-world markets (SEA, LATAM, CIS, RoW).

6. Cost Optimization & Value Delivery

Drive COGS optimization through should-cost modeling, benchmarking, productivity initiatives, and sourcing leverage.

Build and manage a robust value pipeline including cost savings, cash improvements, and risk avoidance.

Track and report savings through approved governance mechanisms.

Partner with Finance on budget planning, standard cost setting, and benefit realization.

7. Medical Affairs & Evidence Generation Procurement

Lead sourcing and supplier governance for RWE, NIS, Clinical Data Acquisition, and Medical Affairs vendors.

Ensure sourcing strategies align with Medical Affairs priorities, compliance standards, and data quality expectations.

Manage contracts and supplier performance to improve timeliness, quality, and cost effectiveness of evidence generation.

Coordinate innovation forums with key vendors to enhance data access and analytical capabilities.

8. Regulatory & Compliance Interface

Ensure procurement activities comply with GxP, FDA, EMA, ICH, and internal governance standards.

Coordinate commercial deliverables linked to regulatory submissions including:

Dossiers

Certificates of Pharmaceutical Product (COPP)

Free Sale Certificates (FSC)

Partner with Regulatory Affairs and Quality teams to manage submission timelines and supplier compliance.

9. Stakeholder Management & Collaboration

Engage cross-functional stakeholders across Supply Chain, Manufacturing, Quality, Regulatory, Medical Affairs, Finance, Legal, and R&D.

Drive stakeholder alignment, transparency, and adherence to category strategies and contracts.

Present category strategies, risks, and performance updates to senior leadership and governance forums.

10. Team Leadership & Capability Building

Lead, coach, and develop category analysts and managers within the team.

Drive capability building in strategic sourcing, supplier governance, evidence-generation procurement, and risk management.

Contribute to procurement transformation initiatives and best-practice standardization.

